Note:
Linux ARM64/AArch64 System Call Definitions

Defines all system call numbers, platform metadata, and registration logic for
Linux running on AArch64 (ARM 64-bit) processors. ARM64 uses the "new-style"
Linux syscall numbering which was established when the architecture was added
to the kernel (v3.7+). Unlike x86_64, ARM64 has no legacy syscalls and uses
*at-suffixed variants for filesystem operations (openat instead of open, etc.).

Syscall convention:
- Syscall number in X8
- Arguments in X0, X1, X2, X3, X4, X5
- Return value in X0
- Invoked via: svc #0

Reference: Linux kernel arch/arm64/include/asm/unistd.h
           (generated from include/uapi/asm-generic/unistd.h)
:End Note

Import "compiler/backend/syscalls/platforms/platform_interface.runa" as PlatformInterface
Import "compiler/backend/syscalls/syscall_registry.runa" as SyscallRegistry
Import "compiler/backend/machine_code/common/machine_code_interface.runa" as MachineCode
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List

